      <body>
         <listPlace>
            <place type="church">
               <placeName xml:lang="gez" corresp="#n1" type="normalized">ʾAzazo Takla Hāymānot</placeName>
               <placeName xml:lang="gez" xml:id="n1" >አዘዞ፡ ተክለ፡ ሃይማኖት</placeName>
               <placeName type="normalized" xml:lang="gez" corresp="#n2">ʾAzazo Za-Dabra Libānos</placeName>
               <placeName xml:lang="gez" xml:id="n2">አዘዞ፡ ዘደብረ፡ ሊባኖስ</placeName>
               <!--              translitterazion in gez to be checked -->
               <country ref="LOC3010Ethiop"/>
               <region notBefore="1991" type="RegionalState" ref="LOC1426Amhara"/>
               <region notAfter="1974" type="Province" ref="LOC1713Bagemd"/>
               <settlement type="zone" ref="LOC6544NorthGondar"/>
               <settlement type="town" ref="LOC1669Azazo"/>
               <location>
                  <geo cert="medium">12.5500 37.4333</geo>
                  <!--                 Geo coord refer to the town of ʾAzazo and are based on Gazeteer -->
               </location>
               <listBibl type="secondary">
                  <bibl><ptr target="bm:BerryEtAl2005EnAeGondar"/></bibl>
                  <bibl><ptr target="bm:Wubneh2003EnAeAzazoTakla"/></bibl>
                  <bibl><ptr target="bm:Wubneh2003EnAeAzazo"/></bibl>
               </listBibl>
               <note>
                  <date type="foundation" cert="low">17th-18th century</date>
                  <desc type="foundation">Local priests believe that it was built by <roleName
                        type="title">ʾaṣe</roleName>
                     <persName ref="PRS4015Fasilada">Fāsiladas</persName> in the <date>17th
                        century</date>, while, according to <persName ref="PRS2916Bruce">James
                           Bruce</persName>, it was built by <persName ref="PRS5617IyasuII">Iyāsu
                        II</persName>, meaning it was built only in the <date>18th century</date>.</desc>
                  <ab type="history">ʾAzazo Takla Hāymānot is one of the so-called 44 churches of
                        <placeName ref="LOC3577Gondar">Gondar</placeName>. It is located in the town
                     of <placeName ref="LOC1669Azazo">ʾAzazo</placeName>, 13 km southwest of
                        <placeName ref="LOC3577Gondar">Gondar</placeName>. This church played an
                     important role in the history of Ethiopian monasticism: following the burning of <placeName ref="LOC2297DabraL">Dabra Libānos</placeName> in <date>1532</date> and the decision to move the monastic community north in the lake <placeName ref="LOC5888Tana">Ṭānā</placeName> area, the monastic
                     community of <placeName ref="LOC2297DabraL">Dabra Libānos</placeName> finally settled in <placeName ref="LOC1669Azazo">ʾAzazo</placeName>.
                     </ab>
                  <ab type="description">ʾAzazo Takla Hāymānot is located at the centre of a
                     hilltop, surrounded by a courtyard and a circular stone wall with a square
                     tower.</ab> 
                     <ab type="tabot">At one hand of the courtyar, there is a semi-circular domed castle wher, according to local traditio, the tabot of <persName ref="PRS6819Mary">Mary</persName> of <placeName ref="LOC2297DabraL">Dabra Libānos</placeName> was first installed when it was moved from <placeName ref="LOC2297DabraL">Dabra Libānos</placeName> to <placeName ref="LOC1669Azazo"
       >ʾAzazo</placeName>, although the tabot's movements are actually quite complicated to reconstruct.</ab>
                     <measure quantity="1"/>
                       </note>
            </place>
